abstract: TACOMA, Washington, May 31. -- The Makah Indians of Neah Bay had a whale hunt Friday which they will long remember. They started out forty-eight strong to secure their season's supply of meat and oil. Their party was rigged out in warlike fashion, filling six big canoes. At daylight Friday, when fifteen miles west of Cape Flattery, they sighted a school of between fifty and sixty whales.

abstract: JACKSONVILLE, June 10. -- A big colored camp meeting near St. Nicholas, below here, was thrown into a panic the other night by the flashing in the sky of the searchlights of the cruisers Wilmington and Vesuvius. The latter was at Mayport, at the mouth of the river, and the other here. The negroes, when they saw the light, fell prostrate and began confessing their sins, crying out that the Angel Gabriel was coming.

abstract: WHEN the Brooklyn Board of Education was organized, May 2, 1843, there were but five schools in the city. abstract: PHILADELPHIA, June 20. -- The monument erected to the memory of Harry Wright, the "Father of Baseball," was unveiled in West Laurel Hill Cemetery this afternoon in the presence of a large crowd of persons. abstract: Agurai is a small town, surrounded with walls of from 40 to 50 feet in height, and built of "tabia," or consolidated rubble. abstract: CHICAGO, June 26. -- Down a long, steep hill at Lakeside eight persons were dragged in an open wagon behind a maddened runaway horse this noon. At the bottom of the hill is a deep ditch and into this the party was thrown beneath the overturned wagon. They were members of the First Presbyterian Church of Evanston, and were on their way to attend the annual picnic of the Sunday school given in Hubbard's Woods.
